<strong>IN&#45;TEXT CITATION</strong>
<br>
<br>
Cite the original publication date and the date of the translation.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	Johnson (1984/2020) indicated that&hellip;
	<br>
	Alternatively: A recent study (Johnson, 1984/2020) indicated that&hellip;
</blockquote>
<br>
When the author is referred to more than once, in the same paragraph, cite the work the first time that 
it is referred to in your writing. Once the work is cited, it is not necessary to include the citation 
again, as long as it is clear that you are referring to the same work and that it cannot be confused 
with other sources being paraphrased. Repeat the citation again, if the paraphrase continues into the 
next paragraph.  
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	In a recent study, Johnson (1984/2020) showed that&hellip; Johnson also found that&hellip;
</blockquote>
<br>
If you are using a direct quotation, consisting of fewer than 40 words, enclose the quote using double 
quotation marks and include page numbers.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	Johnson (1984/2020) observed that generally, &#34;technology&#45;assisted learning has grown in 
	popularity with adolescents&#34; (p. 34).
	<br>
	Alternatively: We can observe that generally, &#34;technology&#45;assisted learning has grown in 
	popularity with adolescents&#34; (Johnson, 1984/2020, p. 34).
</blockquote>
<br>
If the quotation is greater than 40 words, the quote is displayed in a double spaced, indented 
block at 1.27cm from the left margin. Do not use double quotation marks to enclose a block quotation.
